    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"blobsim: an energy-conserving world of blobs\"\njupyter: brainvomit\nexecute:\n  echo: false\n  warning: false\n---\n\n> _Scaffold — prose and interpretation to be filled in. Headings follow the order\n> of discovery; the charts and animations are seeded from a real run._\n\n## What it is\n\n`blobsim` is a small world that runs on a grid. Each cell can hold one **blob** — a\nsimple creature with an energy level. Step by step, every blob senses its\nneighbours, picks an action (move, eat, reproduce, or rest), and pays for it in\nenergy. Blobs that run out of energy die; well-fed ones reproduce. The grid itself\nholds energy that blobs eat and that may or may not replenish over time.\n\nThe one rule the whole world obeys is **conservation of energy**: energy is never\ncreated or destroyed, only moved between blobs, the grid, and a \"spent\" pile. That\nsingle constraint is what makes the world's behaviour predictable — and checkable.\n\n<!-- TODO: what question this world is meant to explore. -->\n\n## How it is designed\n\nThe grid wraps around at the edges (a blob walking off the right side reappears on\nthe left). Every step runs the same fixed sequence:\n\n> observe → decide → resolve who-goes-where → charge energy → act → absorb from the\n> grid → update the environment → remove the dead → record\n\nA few deliberate choices:\n\n- **Energy ledger.** A running tally checks, every single step, that all the energy\n  still adds up — so a bug that quietly leaks energy can't hide.\n- **Repeatable.** The same starting seed always produces the exact same run.\n- **Swappable pieces.** A blob's behaviour (\"rules\"), the environment's behaviour\n  (decaying vs. replenishing), and how movement conflicts are settled can each be\n  swapped out without touching the rest.\n\n<!-- TODO: more on the rules/sensing model and the action costs, in your words. -->\n\n## Inspiration\n\nIt starts from Conway's *Game of Life* — cells on a grid that live or die by their\nneighbours — and asks what happens when each cell becomes an individual that has to\n*earn its living*: carry energy, spend it to act, and starve if it can't. The result\nsits somewhere between a cellular automaton and a tiny ecology.\n\n<!-- TODO: the personal hook — why this was worth building. -->\n\n\n\n## The world in motion\n\nA finite grid with no replenishment can only end one way — the blobs eat through\nthe available energy and die out:\n\n![Two kinds of blob draw down a finite grid until none are left.](images/blobsim/sc1_decay_extinction.gif)\n\nHere is one run's population and total energy over time:\n\n::: {#cell-live-sim .cell execution_count=2}\n\n::: {#live-sim .cell-output .cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div>            <script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/mathjax/2.7.5/MathJax.js?config=TeX-AMS-MML_SVG\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">if (window.MathJax && window.MathJax.Hub && window.MathJax.Hub.Config) {window.MathJax.Hub.Config({SVG: {font: \"STIX-Web\"}});}</script>                <script type=\"text/javascript\">window.PlotlyConfig = {MathJaxConfig: 'local'};</script>\n        <script charset=\"utf-8\" src=\"https://cdn.plot.ly/plotly-3.0.1.min.js\"></script>                <div id=\"01e5def8-f09a-47c8-8440-6bc4ef4c266e\" class=\"plotly-graph-div\" style=\"height:380px; width:100%;\"></div>            <script type=\"text/javascript\">                window.PLOTLYENV=window.PLOTLYENV || {};                                if (document.getElementById(\"01e5def8-f09a-47c8-8440-6bc4ef4c266e\")) {                    Plotly.newPlot(                        \"01e5def8-f09a-47c8-8440-6bc4ef4c266e\",                        [{\"name\":\"population\",\"x\":{\"dtype\":\"i2\",\"bdata\":\"\\u002fAIAAgQCCAIMAhACFAIYAhwCIAIkAigCLAIwAjQCOAI8AkACRAJIAkwCUAJUAlgCXAJgAmQCaAJsAnACdAJ4AnwCgAKEAogCjAKQApQCmAKcAqACpAKoAqwCsAK0ArgCvALAAsQCyALMAtAC1ALYAtwC4ALkAugC7ALwAvQC+AL8AwADBAMIAwwDEAMUAxgDHAA==\"},\"y\":{\"dtype\":\"i2\