\":true,\"ticks\":\"\",\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"gridwidth\":2},\"yaxis\":{\"backgroundcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"gridcolor\":\"white\",\"linecolor\":\"white\",\"showbackground\":true,\"ticks\":\"\",\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"gridwidth\":2},\"zaxis\":{\"backgroundcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"gridcolor\":\"white\",\"linecolor\":\"white\",\"showbackground\":true,\"ticks\":\"\",\"zerolinecolor\":\"white\",\"gridwidth\":2}},\"shapedefaults\":{\"line\":{\"color\":\"#2a3f5f\"}},\"annotationdefaults\":{\"arrowcolor\":\"#2a3f5f\",\"arrowhead\":0,\"arrowwidth\":1},\"geo\":{\"bgcolor\":\"white\",\"landcolor\":\"#E5ECF6\",\"subunitcolor\":\"white\",\"showland\":true,\"showlakes\":true,\"lakecolor\":\"white\"},\"title\":{\"x\":0.05},\"mapbox\":{\"style\":\"light\"},\"margin\":{\"b\":0,\"l\":0,\"r\":0,\"t\":30}}},\"margin\":{\"l\":0,\"r\":0,\"t\":10,\"b\":0},\"legend\":{\"orientation\":\"h\",\"y\":1.15},\"barmode\":\"group\",\"height\":340,\"yaxis\":{\"title\":{\"text\":\"value\"}}},                        {\"responsive\": true}                    ).then(function(){\n                            \nvar gd = document.getElementById('7a8dd7fc-7933-4e89-98a8-43568fa0d006');\nvar x = new MutationObserver(function (mutations, observer) {{\n        var display = window.getComputedStyle(gd).display;\n        if (!display || display === 'none') {{\n            console.log([gd, 'removed!']);\n            Plotly.purge(gd);\n            observer.disconnect();\n        }}\n}});\n\n// Listen for the removal of the full notebook cells\nvar notebookContainer = gd.closest('#notebook-container');\nif (notebookContainer) {{\n    x.observe(notebookContainer, {childList: true});\n}}\n\n// Listen for the clearing of the current output cell\nvar outputEl = gd.closest('.output');\nif (outputEl) {{\n    x.observe(outputEl, {childList: true});\n}}\n\n                        })                };            </script>        </div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\n<!-- TODO: comment on how closely observation tracks prediction. -->\n\n## What the runs show\n\n### A single blob's lifespan\n\nLeft alone on a draining grid, a blob lives a predictable number of steps on\naverage — close to what the energy math says it should.\n\n<!-- TODO: the two-phase intuition (active while it can afford to move, then resting\nuntil it starves). -->\n\n### Boom, then bust\n\nGive blobs a rich grid and they multiply fast — until the crowd outstrips the food\nand the population collapses.\n\n![A population explodes to fill the grid, then crashes.](images/blobsim/sc4_boom_bust.gif)\n\n<!-- TODO: why the peak is set by the size of the grid, not the total energy. -->\n\n### Settling at a carrying capacity\n\nWith energy replenishing, the population stops growing at a stable level — and it\nreaches roughly the same level whether it starts crowded or sparse.\n\n![Starting crowded, the population relaxes toward a steady level.](images/blobsim/sc5_dense.gif)\n\n<!-- TODO: the surprise — the steady level lands ~25% above the simple prediction,\nbecause real blobs spread out and waste fewer moves on collisions than the math\nassumes. -->\n\n### A lone blob's energy\n\nA single blob on a rich, replenishing grid quickly fills up to its maximum and\nstays pinned there.\n\n<!-- TODO. -->\n\n## Competition between kinds\n\nPut two kinds of blob on the same grid and they compete for the same energy:\n\n![Two kinds of blob compete for one grid.](images/blobsim/c3_competition.gif)\n\n<!-- TODO: who wins, and what decides it. -->\n\n## What I took away, in order\n\n<!-- TODO: ordered takeaways, e.g.\n1. Conservation is the backbone — every check is ultimately energy bookkeeping.\n2. On a finite grid, extinction is guaranteed; reproduction only moves energy around.\n3. Crowding, not total energy, caps the population at its peak.\n4. The simplest population prediction runs low because it over-counts collisions.\n-->\n\n",
